INSERT INTO `branches` VALUES (2,'HSCS3002 History of Science Technology and Industry (2017-18)',1,7,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 11:41:55','2017-11-19 11:43:08'),(3,'ME3-HECM Embedded C for Microcontrollers (2017-2018)',1,7,0,1,'Aims\r\n\r\nThis course aims to introduce students who are proficient in MATLAB programming to the C programming language: amongst the most widely-used ever amongst programming languages, and one which provides an excellent foundation for learning others (e.g. C++ and JavaScript). It also aims to develop, from the basic knowledge of mechatronics provided in ME2, an ability to build mechatronic systems containing typical sensors and actuators that are controlled by a microcontroller programmed in C.',1,'2017-11-19 11:42:02','2017-11-19 12:30:41'),(4,'ME3-HLTR Literature Research Project (2017-2018)',1,7,0,1,'Aims\r\nTo develop efficient use of the extensive facilities available for research on a given subject;\r\nTo develop a critical attitude to information sources, an ethical attitude to attributing them and a systematic method for citing them;\r\nTo stimulate interest in a given subject by studying it in depth.',1,'2017-11-19 11:42:10','2017-11-19 12:48:40'),(5,'ME3-HSDP System Design and Optimisation (2017-2018)',1,7,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 11:42:17','2017-11-19 11:43:08'),(6,'ME3-HSTAT Statistics (2017-2018)',1,7,0,1,'Aims\r\nTo show that statistical procedures can be confidently applied and the results reported in a professional manner revealing both good understanding and interpretation.',1,'2017-11-19 11:42:27','2017-11-19 13:56:33'),(7,'ME3 (2017-2018)',1,0,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 11:42:54','2017-11-19 11:43:08'),(8,'ME3-MDMT Design Make and Test Project (2017-2018)',1,7,0,1,'Key Dates:\r\n 	 \r\nQuality Plan - 10th November 2017\r\n\r\nProgress Report - 12th February 2018\r\n\r\nFinal Report - 7th June 2018\r\n\r\nLogbook - 7th June 2018\r\n\r\nPoster - 7th June 2018\r\n\r\nSeminar Week begins - 11th June 2018\r\n\r\nExhibition - 12th June 2018',1,'2017-11-19 11:43:21','2017-11-19 14:57:12'),(9,'ME3-MMSD Machine System Dynamics (2017-2018)',1,7,0,1,'ME3-MMSD Module Description and Aims\r\n\r\nThe course will aim to enable students to evaluate the dynamics response requirements of a proposed machine design and to produce workable proposals for its safe and effective operation. It will build on the second year Mechatronics and Solid Mechanics courses, introducing a greater range of examples where the dynamics response of a machine must be controlled and making the link between vibration and fatigue failure. This will involve some new subject matter in the vibration of continuous systems, rotor dynamics, signal processing and control analysis. Key aspects of the course will be practical demonstrations of control systems and students solving realistic problems using MATLAB. They will also deal with realistic problems involving the assessment of the fatigue life of structures subject to vibration and static loading.',1,'2017-11-19 11:43:28','2017-11-19 15:08:36'),(10,'ME3-MTDE Thermodynamics and Energy (2017-2018)',1,7,0,1,'Aims\r\n\r\nTo enable students to explore advanced concepts in applied thermodynamics and energy supply in the context of UK commitments for reduction of carbon dioxide emissions under the Kyoto protocol and other environmental, commercial and strategic constraints.\r\n\r\nThe current course contains elements that are best covered by selective reading of different texts. The recommended text books are given in the attached document.',1,'2017-11-19 11:43:35','2017-11-19 15:43:31'),(11,'ME2 (2016-2017)',1,0,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 11:44:30','2017-11-19 11:44:30'),(12,'ME2-HCPT Computing (2016-2017)',1,11,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 11:44:43','2017-11-19 11:44:43'),(13,'ME2-HDMF Design and Manufacture (2016-2017)',1,11,0,1,'The ME2 Design and Manufacture course offers students two major engineering projects in which to develop their skills and knowledge of engineering design. \r\nThe first project concerns the design, manufacture and test of a highly loaded rotating machine. This project requires integration of engineering skills and knowledge in dynamics, materials, CAD, manufacture and project management. The project is supported by lectures and tutorials in design, machine elements and CAD over the first five weeks of term. In order to provide you with sufficient time in the workshop the engineering drawings for this project need to be completed by week 5 after which you get scheduled access to the workshop to enable you to manufacture the various components that make up your design.\r\nThe second project, which is undertaken individually, involves the engineering design of a cordless hand-tool for mass manufacture. This project provides an opportunity for you to undertake the complete engineering design of a product. The individual project is introduced at the end of autumn term, when the main work for the group project has been finished.',1,'2017-11-19 11:44:50','2017-11-19 18:32:45'),(14,'ME2-HDYN Dynamics (2016-2017)',1,11,0,1,'Aims\r\n\r\n    To enable students to master essential basic topics in vibrations and dynamics;\r\n    To contribute to the development of their analytical, design and communication skills.\r\n\r\nSyllabus\r\n\r\nVibrations: Free vibration of single-degree-of-freedom undamped and damped systems, resonance, natural frequency, damping, forced vibration of single-degree-of-freedom systems, base excitation, vibration isolation, vibration transmission, introduction to multi-degree-of-freedom systems.\r\n\r\nDynamics: Work-done-energy equation, general plane motion with translation and rotation, impulse-linear momentum, angular impulse-angular momentum, impact, generalized angular impulse-angular momentum, simple gyroscopic motion',1,'2017-11-19 11:44:56','2017-11-20 17:40:31'),(15,'ME2-HFMX Fluid Mechanics (2016-2017)',1,11,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 11:45:02','2017-11-19 11:45:02'),(16,'ME2-HHTR Heat Transfer (2016-2017)',1,11,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 11:45:08','2017-11-19 11:45:08'),(17,'ME2-HMATL Materials (2016-2017)',1,11,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 11:45:14','2017-11-19 11:45:14'),(18,'ME2-HMBE Management and Business for Engineers (2016-2017)',1,11,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 11:45:20','2017-11-19 11:45:20'),(19,'ME2-HMTH Mathematics (2016-2017)',1,11,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 11:45:29','2017-11-19 11:45:29'),(20,'ME2-HMTX Mechatronics (2016-2017)',1,11,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 11:45:35','2017-11-19 11:45:35'),(21,'ME2-HSAN Stress Analysis (2016-2017)',1,11,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 11:45:42','2017-11-19 11:45:42'),(22,'ME2-HTHD Thermodynamics (2016-2017)',1,11,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 11:45:49','2017-11-19 11:45:49'),(26,'Course readings and resources',1,2,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:05:21','2017-11-19 12:05:21'),(27,'Sample essays',1,2,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:05:30','2017-11-19 12:05:30'),(28,'Session 1',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:05:51','2017-11-19 12:05:51'),(29,'Session 2',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:06:04','2017-11-19 12:06:04'),(30,'Session 3',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:06:20','2017-11-19 12:06:20'),(31,'Session 4',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:06:27','2017-11-19 12:06:27'),(32,'Session 5',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:06:43','2017-11-19 12:06:43'),(33,'Session 6',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:06:53','2017-11-19 12:06:53'),(34,'Session 7',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:07:01','2017-11-19 12:07:01'),(35,'Session 8',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:07:08','2017-11-19 12:07:08'),(36,'Session 9',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:07:14','2017-11-19 12:07:14'),(37,'Session 10',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:07:21','2017-11-19 12:07:21'),(38,'Session 11',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:07:26','2017-11-19 12:07:26'),(39,'Session 12',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:07:33','2017-11-19 12:07:33'),(40,'Session 13',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:07:39','2017-11-19 12:07:39'),(41,'Session 14',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:07:49','2017-11-19 12:07:49'),(42,'Session 15',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:07:57','2017-11-19 12:07:57'),(43,'Session 16',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:08:09','2017-11-19 12:08:09'),(45,'Session 17',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:08:40','2017-11-19 12:08:40'),(46,'Session 18',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:08:47','2017-11-19 12:08:47'),(47,'Session 19',1,26,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:08:53','2017-11-19 12:08:53'),(48,'Lecture notes',1,3,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:28:20','2017-11-19 12:28:20'),(49,'Microchip datasheets',1,3,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:28:28','2017-11-19 12:28:28'),(50,'Programming style and fault finding',1,3,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:28:36','2017-11-19 12:28:36'),(51,'Lab 1: \"Hello, world!\"',1,3,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:28:46','2017-11-19 12:28:46'),(52,'Lab 2: Digital and analogue input/output',1,3,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:29:05','2017-11-19 12:29:05'),(53,'Lab 3: Interrupts and timers',1,3,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:29:14','2017-11-19 12:29:14'),(54,'Lab 4: LCD',1,3,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:29:25','2017-11-19 12:29:25'),(55,'Lab 5: PWM module and motor control',1,3,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:29:35','2017-11-19 12:29:35'),(56,'Lab 6: Serial communication',1,3,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:29:43','2017-11-19 12:29:43'),(57,'Labs 7-10: Course project',1,3,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:29:52','2017-11-19 12:29:52'),(58,'Course Materials',1,4,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:49:50','2017-11-19 12:49:50'),(59,'Literature Research Project Library Tutorial',1,4,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:50:00','2017-11-19 12:50:00'),(60,'Example Research Projects',1,4,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:50:10','2017-11-19 12:50:10'),(61,'Centre for Academic English (CfAE)',1,4,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:50:19','2017-11-19 12:50:19'),(62,'A - Graded Projects',1,60,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:55:04','2017-11-19 12:55:04'),(63,'B - Graded Projects',1,60,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 12:55:13','2017-11-19 12:55:13'),(122,'System Design and Optimisation Course Information',1,5,0,1,'For the goal is not the last, but the best. \r\nAristoteles (Second Book of Physics) (384-322 B.C.)\r\n\r\nquoted in relation to Optimimzation by Professor Panos Papalambros, University of Michigan\r\n\r\nWelcome to ME3-HSDP: System Design and Optimisation!  This course was introduced in 2013-14 as a means of bridging quantitative approaches common to analysis to support qualitative decisions in design.  The purpose, simply stated, is to make students conversant in key mathematical techniques as applied to system design.  In this context, we define a design optimisation problem as one where the \'best\' solution must be chosen from a range of potential options.  As each option may be modeled as a variable, the course introduces empirical measures to find the \'best\' combination for variables for the design.  The course is presented in nine learning modules, outlined below.  \r\n\r\n In this folder you will find general information on the course, its learning outcomes, syllabus, grading scheme, and student feedback from previous sessions.\r\n\r\nCourse Overview\r\nThe purpose of the unit is to introduce the concept of mathematical optimization as applied to system design.  Design, in this context, is viewed in the broad sense capturing problems ranging from engineering (technical) design, to plant operations, to complex processes such as civil planning and infrastructure, to financial modelling.  The course aims at providing students with a first exposure to a rational integration of design methodologies with concepts and techniques of modern optimization theory and practice.  The goal is to enable modelling of constraints and processes in system design such that single and multivariate optimization may be performed to focus on critical measures of performance.   It will stress rigorous, quantitative multidisciplinary design methodology that works with the non-quantitative and creative side of the design process. The objective of the course is to present tools and methodologies for performing system optimization in a multidisciplinary design context. Focus will be on all: (i) the multidisciplinary character of engineering systems, (ii) the creation of reasonable models of such systems, and (iii) tools for optimization, with emphasis on software and numerical analysis.  Students will complete the course conversant with techniques in practice to create appropriate mathematical optimization models and to use analytical and computational techniques to solve them\r\n\r\nAims\r\nThe learning aims of this course include:\r\n\r\nTo introduce the concept and theory of mathematical optimisation.\r\nTo demonstrate the practical use of optimisation in a range of system design problems from engineering (technical) design to complex processes such as civil planning and infrastructure and financial modelling, including non-quantitative and creative aspects of the design process.\r\nTo acquaint students with modelling techniques and solution methods and software to implement them.\r\n\r\nLearning Outcomes\r\nAt the end of the course students should be able to: \r\nFormulate precise engineering problems from ambiguous sources in design\r\nReview relevant literature related to engineering principles and discern critical issues relevant to design problems\r\nImplement mathematical optimization tools in engineering design\r\nFormulate systems engineering problems as mathematical optimization formulations\r\nCharacterize, model, formulate, and solve engineering and/or technical problems such that mathematical tools of optimization may be applied for comparison of key performance parameters.\r\nUtilize programming languages such as Xcel and Matlab to solve convex optimization problems\r\nUndertake research, design, development, procurement, operation and/or maintenance in scientific and/or technical engineering fields in optimization and design\r\nArticulate the impact of engineering and/or technical solutions in global context\r\nInteract with personnel from industry, laboratories, academic institutions and/or other services regarding system design, maintenance, and operation\r\n\r\nTarget Audience\r\nIt is the purpose of this course to introduce system optimization in the context of design.  Students will complete the course conversant in the basic principles necessary to utilize domain knowledge in their area of interest to create models for design optimization in that field, and to implement them in software for critical trade-off comparison. This course is intended for system designers, engineers, program acquisition professionals, analysts and others who need to understand how to think in a “big picture” way for system development using systems engineering and analysis methods in synergy with basic optimization tools.  The material is targeted at students without prior knowledge of optimization who wish to apply optimization in practical design situations or who may pursue advanced research work. The treatment of topics is mathematically rigorous but with an emphasis on practical use. \r\n\r\nTeaching Methods\r\nStudents will receive lectures, reading assignments, and four homework assignments (ranging from discussion board participation to programming/simulation exercises) each week for 11 weeks.  Within this period they are expected to consolidate and enhance the lecture material with private study.  The primary focus of the course is the implementation of optimization models in engineering design, thus an emphasis will be place on coursework.  A final exam will also be incorporated into grading.\r\nLecture notes will be provided throughout the course as they pertain to each lecture.  These notes are divided into sections reflecting the structure of the course in general and the chronology of the lectures.  Each section gives some background, detail and limited worked examples to enable the student to enhance his or her personal learning experience both in the lecture room and outside it. \r\n\r\nLecture Delivery\r\nThe course will consist of 10 2-hour lectures (including problem solving sessions).  There is an optional 1 hour problem solving session (added this year based on feedback from previous years) every 2 weeks as well, though class time will be spent on example problems.\r\n  \r\nCoursework\r\nThere will be 4 pieces of coursework through the term, assigned in Weeks 1, 3, 5, and 9.  The first will be to review current literature and participate in an on-line discussion with the class, while the following 3 will involve simulations for solving optimization problems.   Individual written feedback will be provided for each coursework assignment.\r\n\r\nPrerequisites\r\nThere are no prerequisites for the course, however past student feedback has indicated that a strong proficiency in Matlab and comfort-level with linear algebra and differential equations are very important to the course.  Students without this proficiency will need to spend more time in the early stages of the course in independent study on these topics.  Students are encouraged to contact the instructor if they have any questions as to their background for taking the course.',1,'2017-11-19 13:00:09','2017-11-19 13:05:16'),(123,'Course Material',1,5,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 13:00:23','2017-11-19 13:00:23'),(124,'Panopto Lectures',1,5,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 13:00:31','2017-11-19 13:00:31'),(125,'Topic 1: Introduction to Systems Design',1,5,0,1,'Any one who has passed through the regular gradations of a classical education, and is not made a fool by it, may consider himself as having had a very narrow escape. … Memory .. is the chief faculty called into play, in conning over and repeating lessons by rote .. so that he who has the most of this technical memory, with the least turn for other things, .., will make the most forward school-boy.\r\n\r\n- William Hazlitt (1778-1830), in “On the Ignorance of the Learned”\r\n\r\nTopic 1, hopefully setting the stage for conceptual thinking as opposed to recap, will begin with a review of design, then introduce basic concepts in systems architecting and systems thinking as they relate to engineering.  We will cover system life cycle models and address functional allocation on a very basic level.  On a conceptual level, we will introduce optimisation and its possible role in system development.  As our first lecture, we will of course cover the course philosophy, structure, and grading scheme as well.  Learning outcomes for this topic include:\r\n\r\nTo understand the course goals, philosophy, and delivery\r\nTo establish a basic familiarity with Systems Engineering\r\nTo understand system development models and be able to consider the pros and cons of each as they relate to system design\r\nTo understand the context and importance of optimisation in system design \r\nThere will be 3 lectures, two reading assignments, and one written piece of coursework with this topic.  PDF copies of the slides and reading are included here:',1,'2017-11-19 13:00:40','2017-11-19 13:42:26'),(126,'Topic 2: Introduction to Optimisation',1,5,0,1,'Math is easy; design is hard\r\n\r\n- Jeffery Veen (1968 - )\r\n\r\nTopic 2 will cover an introduction to mathematical concepts in engineering optimisation and design.  We will outline optimisation in an engineering context, discuss key concepts, formulate a process for approaching optimisation problems, and outline approaches to optimisation.  We will also define a set of mathematical preliminaries that should outline any optimisation problem.  We will then introduce our first optimal search method, the Golden Section Search.  Finally, we will cover, by example, some simple optimisation problems to clarify the concepts presented. Learning outcomes for this topic include:\r\n\r\nTo understand the mathematical notation and definitions in optimisation problem formulation\r\nTo understand the basic steps involved in engineering optimisation, in particular the process of converting a  descriptive engineering problem into an optimisation formulation\r\nTo understand the differences between the three fundamental approaches to solving an optimisation problem (calculus-based, enumerative, heuristic)\r\nTo understand the concept of search-methods and the 1-dimensional Golden Section search. \r\nTo understand system development models and be able to consider the pros and cons of each as they relate to system design\r\nTo understand the context and importance of optimisation in system design \r\nTo begin to be able to formulate simple engineering problems as optimal search problems\r\nThere will be 1 lecture (including example problems) and reading assignments from the Aurora text book (electronic copy linked above).\r\n\r\nA PDF copy of the slides is included here.  This week\'s reading will cover Chapter 1 and Chapter 2 in the Aurora text.  These chapters introduce optimisation in engineering design (in a slightly different context than my presentation) and are meant to supplement the lecture.  They will give important prespectives on optimisation and design.',1,'2017-11-19 13:00:49','2017-11-19 13:42:40'),(127,'Topic 3: Modelling and Simulation',1,5,0,1,'All models are wrong .. some are useful\r\n\r\nGeorge E.P. Box (1919-2013), in Empirical Model Building and Response Surfaces\r\n\r\nIn Topic 3, we will build on the mathematical topics from Topic 2 to cover fundamental concepts in modelling and simulation of dynamic systems.  This will be done through the introduction of second order systems, which can be used to capture a very wide range of systems, engineering or otherwise.  We will introduce state space models (which will hopefully look familiar), continue with our work on creating mathematical models from descriptive problems, and move forward with mathematical definitions of critical system characteristics (linearity, causality, etc.).    Finally, we will cover numeric methods of integration to solve any state space model.  At the close of this topic, you should be able to solve almost any dynamically modelled set of differential equations through the creation of a state space model and computer simulation.  Learning outcomes for this topic include:\r\n\r\nIntroducing the similarities between 2nd order systems through examples from mechanical, electrical, and biological systems\r\nIntroducing (reviewing) state space modelling techniques\r\nReviewing classification of systems based on models\r\nReviewing basic numerical integration in the context of modelling and simulation\r\nIntroducing fundamental concepts for basic simulation based on state space models\r\nThere is one set of lecture slides, but we will be solving problems with both the erase board and Matlab.  We will also start the topic with a review of some of Topic 2, so please look over last week\'s notes as well.  You will also be receiving your first programming assignment this week, which will cover all the concepts in Topic 3 and an implementation of the Golden Section Search covered in Topic 2.',1,'2017-11-19 13:00:59','2017-11-19 13:42:53'),(128,'Topic 4: Linear Programming',1,5,0,1,'Narrative is linear, but action has breadth and depth as well as height and is solid.\r\n\r\nThomas Carlyle (1795-1881)\r\n\r\nIn Topic 4, we will introduce the concept of Linear Programming, which is a critical optimization method commonly used in business and engineering for problems constrained by inequalities.  This expected to take two weeks (since we will begin this week with homework review and complete linearization).  We will first cover graphical solutions to two-dimensional problems, and in our second week cover Gauss-Jordan manipulation to solve n-dimensional systems.  Learning outcomes for this topic include:\r\n\r\nUnderstanding how to convert descriptive problems into linear programming optimization problems\r\nGraphically solve any linear optimization problem having two design variables\r\nPlot constraints and identify their feasible/infeasible solutions\r\nIdentify the feasible region/feasible set for the proble\r\nBe able to use Matlab to solve n-dimensional linear programming optimization problems\r\nThere will be two sets of lecture slides, which will be covered over portions of 2 weeks.  Also please make sure to continue on your homework assignments.\r\n\r\nThe reading material provided suplements the lecture (and provided examples worked out in class).',1,'2017-11-19 13:01:11','2017-11-19 13:43:06'),(129,'Topic 5: Emergent Behavior and Decentralized Systems',1,5,0,1,'Ants are the history of social orgaization and the future of computers\r\n\r\nKevin Kelley (1952 - ), in New Rules for the New Economy, Penguin Books, 1999\r\n\r\nThe purpose of Topic 5 is to introduce decentralized systems and emergent behaviour in the context of a design tool for optimization.  So called \'Ant Colony Optimization\' techniques have been the topic of significant growth in the last few years, and the central idea of this module is to build a basic familiarity with the concept.  This is a slight departure from the methods we have discussed; while the methods are heuristic in nature, they are implemented in an entirely decentralized manner based on simple \'agents\' and limited observability.  \r\n\r\nLearning outcomes for this topic include:\r\n\r\nIntroducing and becoming comfortable with the concept of a decentralized system designed to optimize complex tasks\r\nUnderstand the concept of an \'agent\' in the context of decentralized systems\r\nUnderstand how to formulate agent behaviour through the use of Markov chains\r\nBecome comfortable, from an algorithmic perspective, with organizing ant colony optimization problems based on agent-behaviour \r\nUnderstand the importance of random actions, direct and indirect communication on collectives of agents.  \r\nIn addition to the lecture, there is a reading assignment, and a homework assignment (with an accompanying paper related to the assignment).',1,'2017-11-19 13:01:21','2017-11-19 13:43:17'),(130,'Topic 6: Evolutionary Algorithms',1,5,0,1,'Once evolution gets a good basic design, it tends to throw away the variants and concentrate on the near-infinite diversity within that design.\r\n\r\nDan Simmons (1948- ), in Rise of Endymion\r\n\r\nIn this topic, we will introduce evolutionary algorithms as an optimization tool.  As discussed to date, existing search procedures for optimization problems may be divided into three main categories: calculus-based, enumerative, and heuristic .  Calculus-based procedures use either analytical or numeric models of the solution space as the basis for the search.  Enumerative or “brute force” procedures search systematically and do not incorporate any sophisticated methods to reduce the problem space or refine proposed solutions.  Heuristic procedures attempt to improve on the search efficiency of enumerative methods without direct incorporation of models of the solution space, which are often unavailable.\r\n\r\nA class of heuristic searching methods based upon simulated evolution, known broadly as Evolutionary Algorithms (EAs), has become popular recently for discrete optimization problems characterized by many local minima in nondifferentiable, discontinuous or constrained problem spaces.  These techniques are population oriented; successive populations of feasible solutions are generated in a stochastic manner following laws similar to that of natural selection.  This contrasts with standard techniques that normally follow a single trajectory repeatedly until a satisfactory solution is reached.  In the evolutionary approach, multiple stochastic solution trajectories proceed simultaneously through processing interactions mimicking genetic exchange, thus progressing towards one or more regions of the search space.  These approaches are justified by the fact that a population-oriented algorithm will automatically store time-sampled replicas of the profile for the function being optimized, providing important clues to its global structure.\r\n\r\nEvolutionary approaches work well when calculus based solutions may become trapped within local minima and objective functions do not have differentiable models of problem spaces or are characterized by sharp discontinuities.  They also work well when a variety of optimization criteria or allow changes in these standards without changing the characteristics of the planner or the search map.  Evolutionary approaches, on the other hand, can handle a variety of optimization goals and are very tolerant to the form of the evaluation function.  Functions to be optimized need not be differentiable or continuous; evolutionary path planning approaches are flexible to changes in the environment and are robust to uncertainties, making them well suited to multiconstraint optimization problems. \r\n\r\nThere are a very wide range and breadth of approaches in implementing evolutionary optimization techniques.  The goal of this topic is to introduce you to these and begin to become comfortable with the concept of population based optimization.  Learning objectives include:\r\n\r\nUnderstanding the concept of an evolutionary algorithm in the context of solving optimizaiton problems\r\nLearning the basic steps common to all evolutionary algorithm implementations\r\nUnderstanding basic evolutionary optimization operations such as crossover, mutation, and progressive generational improvement\r\nUnderstanding how to transfer candidate solutions into a form such that evolutionary operations may be performed on them in an optimization process\r\nBeing able to identify when evolutionary approaches make sense for an optimization problem as opposed to calculus-based or enumerative solution\r\nThere are several reading assignments this week, and your final programming assignment will be given out (due in 3 weeks) with a linear programming problem and using the genetic algorithm optimzation tool.',1,'2017-11-19 13:01:29','2017-11-19 13:43:29'),(131,'Topic 7: Constrained Optimization',1,5,0,1,'Every constraint, even dullness, frees up a new design\r\n\r\nRichard Powers (1957-)\r\n\r\nIn Topic 7, we will go further with constrained optimization and introduce Lagrange Multipliers.  This is a critical concept in optimization problems that have nonlinear functions and constraints that limit our options in linear programming.  There will be two lectures in this topic.  The first covers Lagrange Multipliers and their use in constrained optimziation.  The second (in the following week) will go into optimality conditions and the Karesh-Kuhn-Tucker Optimality Criteria.  \r\n\r\nChapter 4 of your electronic text gives a good overview of much of this material.\r\n\r\nLearning outcomes for this topic include:\r\n\r\nFormulating constrained nonlinear optimization problems\r\nUnderstanding Lagrange multipliers and their use in optimizaiton problems\r\nUnderstanding how to check optimality of a given piont for constrained problems\r\nUnderstanding the Karesh-Kuhn-Tucker (KKT) Optimality Criteria and being able to check potential extrema as KKT points',1,'2017-11-19 13:01:38','2017-11-19 13:43:40'),(132,'Topic 8: Descent Methods and Mimization',1,5,0,1,'Searching is half the fun: life is much more manageable when thought of as a scavenger hunt as opposed to a surprise party.\r\n\r\nJimmy Buffett (1946 - )\r\n\r\nThe purpose of this topic is to introduce Descent Methods and gradient based search techniqes.  We will cover Steepest Descent, Conjugate-Gradient Methods, and Newton Methods.  Our focus will be on unconstrained problems here, but all these methods can be modified to address constrained problems.  \r\n\r\nLearning objectives include:\r\n\r\nUnderstanding basic similarities between all gradient based search algorithms\r\nUnderstanding how steepest descent and Newton search methods work\r\nUnderstanding the difference between algorithms relying on 2nd derivative methods (Hessian)\r\nUnderstanding the strengths and weaknesses between approaches of this nature',1,'2017-11-19 13:01:45','2017-11-19 13:43:51'),(133,'Topic 9: Economic Cost Comparison',1,5,0,1,'There is no comparison between that which is lost by not succeeding and that which is lost by not trying.\r\nFrances Bacon, 1561-1626\r\n\r\nIn Topic 9, we will cover elementary cost comparison.  There is an entire field of \'cost engineering\' which is gaining prominence today that draws heavily from optimization.  The purpose of this section is to give you a very brief introduction to time sereis cost comparison.  There is a short reading section for your reference that will complement the lecture material.  Your basic formula for all the material in this section is the sum of one and the interest rate to the +n or -n power, where n is the amount of periods the interest is compounded.  The reading explains how to apply this in different contexts.',1,'2017-11-19 13:01:53','2017-11-19 13:44:01'),(134,'Review Material',1,5,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 13:02:02','2017-11-19 13:02:02'),(135,'Topic 1 Past Exam Papers',1,6,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 13:54:53','2017-11-19 13:54:53'),(136,'Topic 2 Handouts',1,6,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 13:54:59','2017-11-19 13:54:59'),(137,'Topic 3 Exercises',1,6,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 13:55:05','2017-11-19 13:55:05'),(138,'Topic 4 Statistical tables & formula sheet',1,6,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 13:55:10','2017-11-19 13:55:10'),(139,'Topic 5 Practice exam questions',1,6,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 13:55:16','2017-11-19 13:55:16'),(140,'Topic 6 Slides',1,6,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 13:55:22','2017-11-19 13:55:22'),(141,'Topic 7 Course Work',1,6,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 13:55:32','2017-11-19 13:55:32'),(142,'Panopto',1,6,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 13:55:43','2017-11-19 13:55:43'),(144,'Data',1,137,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 14:10:09','2017-11-19 14:10:09'),(145,'Exercise Sheets',1,137,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 14:10:28','2017-11-19 14:10:28'),(146,'Matlab',1,137,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 14:10:40','2017-11-19 14:10:40'),(147,'R',1,137,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 14:10:46','2017-11-19 14:10:46'),(148,'Solutions',1,145,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 14:19:28','2017-11-19 14:19:28')