,'2017-11-19 16:37:41','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(304,'Examples',1,270,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:37:52','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(305,'Lecturer Sildes',1,270,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:37:59','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(306,'Chapters 1 and 2: Introduction & Review',1,271,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:38:34','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(307,'Chapter 3: Power Cycles and Plant',1,271,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:38:43','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(308,'Chapter 4: Gas and Gas-Vapour Mixtures',1,271,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:38:49','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(309,'The Complete Notes',1,271,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:38:59','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(310,'Course materials',1,272,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:39:40','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(311,'Tutorial 0',1,273,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:49:04','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(312,'Tutorial 1',1,273,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:49:14','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(313,'Tutorial 2',1,273,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:49:20','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(314,'Tutorial 3',1,273,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:49:26','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(315,'Tutorial 4',1,273,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:49:33','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(316,'Tutorial 5',1,273,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:49:39','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(317,'Tutorial 6',1,273,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:49:46','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(318,'Suggested solutions',1,311,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:50:53','2017-11-19 16:52:22'),(319,'Suggested solutions',1,312,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:56:29','2017-11-19 16:56:29'),(320,'Suggested solutions',1,313,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:56:43','2017-11-19 16:56:43'),(321,'Suggested solutions',1,314,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:56:49','2017-11-19 16:56:49'),(322,'Suggested solutions',1,315,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:56:54','2017-11-19 16:56:54'),(323,'Suggested solutions',1,316,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:57:01','2017-11-19 16:57:01'),(324,'Suggested solutions',1,317,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 16:57:08','2017-11-19 16:57:08'),(325,'Files needed',1,313,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 17:01:04','2017-11-19 17:01:04'),(326,'Lecture Slides, Notes, etc',1,13,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 18:35:58','2017-11-19 18:35:58'),(327,'eScooter project',1,13,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 18:36:09','2017-11-19 18:36:09'),(328,'Handtool project',1,13,0,1,'Report - some advise and general guidelines.\r\n\r\nBelow some pointers and advice regarding reporting. Like most other things in design (and in life) there is not a single are many ways to do things right.\r\n\r\n1 – The \"flow of the report\": It should not be difficult for the reader to understand the text. The relationships between parts of the report should be obvious. There will be unavoidable situations where this will not be self-evident, so explain how this fits and why you are switching direction.\r\n\r\n2 – Structure and organisation: We are looking to see that you understand the correct design process, we are not expecting a chronological account. Write the report in a logical order!\r\n\r\n3 – Figures, Diagrams and Tables: Discuss and Explain. Do not expect the reader to conclude exactly what you intended to communicate, but explain what the diagram shows and what the reader should conclude.\r\n\r\n4 – Figures, Diagrams and Tables – 2: These need captions and should be referenced from the text, even if that is a single line that states \"Table 2 illustrates XYZ\". However, it is unlikely that that is all that needs to be said – see point 3, above. Additionally, please make sure the cross referencing is numeric and correct (i.e. “as shown in figure 1”). Note also that statements such as \"as shown in the figure below\" is rather pointless, because unless this is the last page, there will be many figures “below”.\r\n\r\n5 – Images: Make sure that these are clear, with the relevant dimensions, resolution and contrast. An example from previous years was a thumbnail of an A4 page with the statement \"figure 4 shows how the design process progressed\". It does not because (a) the image only shows a small collection of blurred pixels and (b) I won’t necessarily understand your reasoning… discuss and explain!\r\n\r\n6 – Appendices: An appendix is a piece of information that adds to a report but is not necessary for the understanding of that report. The Litmus test is to imagine that, before the reader reads the report, they will tear off the appendices and throw them in the bin. Does the report still work? If not, then it needs reworking.\r\n\r\n7 – Make sure that the final copy flows properly - see point 1 above! Then proofread it. Then have someone else proofread it, then proof read it again!\r\n\r\n8 - The page limit can be quite restrictive and discussion and explanation is important. This means you will need to keep things concise. Don’t state the obvious, don\'t say the same thing twice in different ways and don’t use 100 words when 20 will do.',1,'2017-11-19 18:36:19','2017-11-20 12:59:54'),(329,'Resit & SQT',1,13,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 18:36:31','2017-11-19 18:36:31'),(330,'ME1 information and notes',1,327,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 19:10:20','2017-11-19 19:10:20'),(331,'CAD models',1,327,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 19:10:31','2017-11-19 19:10:31'),(332,'Scooter feedback',1,327,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-19 19:10:41','2017-11-19 19:10:41'),(333,'Additional information regarding mechanism and handtools',1,328,0,1,'Design Guidance for Injection Mouldings\r\n\r\nFor injection moulding, the following basic rules can be used as a rule of thumb:\r\n\r\nUse a uniform wall thickness throughout the moulded part. This will minimise any issues, such as sinking and warping and facilitate filling of the mould and reduce the cycle time.\r\nUse large radii. The inside radius should be at least the same as the material thickness, if not more\r\nChoose the minimum thickness that matches all requirements of the part, i.e. process, material, and product design. This ensures rapid cooling, short cycle times and minimum mass - so minimum part cost.\r\nDesign the product so that it enables easy withdrawal from the mould: use a draft angle (taper) in the direction of motion of the mould when opening and closing.\r\n\r\nRibs will improve the stiffness of the component, thus avoiding the need to use thick sections (and thus mass, material costs and cycle time costs)\r\n\r\nCommonly used design elements in injection mouldings include Ribs, Bosses, Counter bores/sinks, Inserts, Self-Tapping Screw holes, Snap Latches and Living Hinge',1,'2017-11-20 12:00:27','2017-11-20 13:02:08'),(334,'Various Links and Machine Videos',1,333,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-20 12:00:47','2017-11-20 12:00:47'),(335,'Photos of the inside of some example consumer products',1,333,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-20 12:01:14','2017-11-20 12:01:14'),(336,'ME2 Extended Notes on Various Machine Elements',1,333,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-20 12:01:31','2017-11-20 12:04:04'),(337,'Topic 1 - Lectures and Panopto Recordings',1,14,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-20 17:37:13','2017-11-20 17:37:13'),(338,'Topic 2 - Handouts',1,14,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-20 17:37:31','2017-11-20 17:37:31'),(339,'Topic 3 - Lab Documents',1,14,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-20 17:37:43','2017-11-20 17:37:43'),(340,'Selected panopto videos from previous years',1,14,0,1,NULL,1,'2017-11-20 17:38:00','2017-11-20 17:38:00'),(341,'Lecture Notes',1,278,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-20 18:19:14','2017-11-20 18:19:14'),(342,'Panopto recordings 2016-17 - please use these ones',1,278,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-20 18:19:45','2017-11-20 18:19:45'),(343,'Panopto recordings 2015-16',1,278,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-20 18:19:53','2017-11-20 18:19:53'),(344,'Panopto recordings 2014-15',1,278,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-20 18:19:59','2017-11-20 18:19:59'),(345,'Panopto recordings 2013-14',1,278,0,5,NULL,1,'2017-11-20 18:20:05','2017-11-20 18:20:05');
